16- Renal and urinary 

Wednesday, October 4, 2017 

7:30 PM 

Identify the position, relationships and surface anatomy of the kidney 

The kidneys are on the posterior abdominal wall, embedded in perinephric fat. They have a retroperitoneal origin. Note that the right kidney is lower due to the position of the liver. Note that the ureters go downward out of the kidneys. 

Identify the size, surfaces, borders and poles 

The kidneys are about 12cm long, 6cm wide and 3 cm thick. Both kidneys usually lie between T12 and L2 (Adrenal glands T11-T12). It has dorsal contact with the diaphragm, psoas major and quadratus lumborum (back muscle). The ventral surface differs: the left kidney touches the tail of pancreas and splenic flexure, whilst the right kidney touches the liver and hepatic flexure. The rostral (cranial) and caudal poles simply refer to the upper and lower surfaces of the kidney. 

 

Note: renal arteries and veins at L1 

 

Identify the cortex, medulla, renal pelvis and renal sinus; the renal pyramids and papillae; the columns and medullary rays; the major and minor calices; and the renal capsule. 

 

To note: 

-Papillae are the sites from which the renal pyramids empty urine into the minor calyx 

-Pyramid = medulla 

-"Medullary" in medullary rays refers to their destination, and this simply refers to the radially-oriented portions of the nephron tubules 

 

Describe and identify the blood supply and venous drainage of the kidneys 

 

 

Identify the position of the renal vein, renal artery, and renal pelvis and the hilum- this will indicate if you are looking at a left or right kidney 

Vein is most anterior followed by the artery in most cases, but this is subject to variation at the hilum. The renal pelvis/ureter is always the most posterior.  

 

Identify and describe course of the ureters in abdomen: understand and see those "kinks" and relationships with gonadal vessels, ovaries and appendix 

Gonadal vessels pass anterior to the ureters. Common iliac passes behind the gonadal vessels, at the point where it branches into internal and external iliac. The appendix is small and lies anterior to the ureter, and appendicitis can cause ureteral obstruction. The ovary likewise passes over the ureter, and ovarian cysts can cause ureteral obstruction. 

 

Study the relationship of the suprarenal glands with kidneys, diaphragm, liver, and identify their blood supply 

The suprarenal glands are also covered in perinephric fat. The inferior phrenic arteries branch off to give the superior suprarenal arteries. An independent branch off the aorta, the middle suprarenal artery, also exists. The inferior suprarenal arteries branch off the renal arteries. The right suprarenal vein connects straight to the IVC, whilst the left suprarenal vein attaches to the left renal vein.
